{
  "doc_id": "23697",
  "text": "A review of filament stretching rheometers can be found in Galindo-Rosales et al. [CITATION_1] . A sample of liquid is placed between two platens (i.e. the ends of two rods), and the platens moved apart either (i) at controlled separating speed, imparting a known strain rate, or (ii) rapidly, causing the formation of a filament which thins under capillary action. The latter mode, shown in Figure 1 (a), known as CaBER™ (capillary break-up extensional rheometry [CITATION_2] ) mode, is used here. A high speed camera and image analysis software monitors the filament diameter at its mid-point, D, over time, t. The filament will break at the mid-point under pure extension. Gravity has negligible effect with the devices employed here, as the dimensions give Bond numbers « 1 [CITATION_3] ; this is discussed after Equation [CITATION_4] .",
